Read more How to Increase Energy Production with Age | AgelessRx Skip to content Search for: Here’s what we’ll cover in this blog post: The connection between energy and aging Why mitochondria are your body’s secret powerhouses How ATP keeps you feeling young and vibrant Easy tips to keep your energy levels high as you age Ever feel like aging is slowly draining your energy? What if you could hang onto that same energy you felt when you were twenty and increase energy production as you age? According to the energy maintenance theory of aging , it’s possible! The key lies in keeping your cells energized, as those who age best have cells that excel at maintaining energy production over time. The driving force behind this energy? Your mitochondria—the powerhouses of our cells . These tiny engines produce ATP—the fuel your body needs to repair, grow, and keep your muscles and brain in top shape. As we age, our mitochondria slow down. Less ATP means less energy, and soon our bodies feel like they’re running on a low battery. This can show up as weaker muscles, brain fog, and a higher chance of illness. The good news? If we keep our mitochondria healthy, we can stay sharp, strong, and energized for years to come. But what exactly happens to our mitochondria as we age, and how does it impact the aging process? Mitochondrial Dysfunction and Aging Mitochondrial dysfunction is one of the hallmarks of aging . As we age, our mitochondria weaken, unlike the pristine powerhouses you’d find in a toddler’s cells. Damaged mitochondria struggle to produce enough energy, leading to fatigue and other signs of aging. When our cells can’t produce the energy they need, everything slows down—immune function, metabolism, and even brain performance. However, improving mitochondrial efficiency can not only help our bodies keep up with life’s demands, but it may even slow down the aging process. Feeling Fatigued? It Might Be a Bigger Deal Everyone gets tired, but chronic fatigue could signal a bigger issue. Fatigue can be an early warning sign of conditions like heart disease, diabetes, or even cancer. What’s going on behind the scenes? It might be a lack of cellular energy with declining ATP production that’s driving that ongoing tiredness. By improving mitochondrial health and working to boost ATP production, you can give your body the energy it needs to fight fatigue and stay resilient against disease as you age. Whether with supplements or lifestyle changes, supporting ATP synthesis can help you feel more energy and even slow down the effects of aging. How Can You Boost Mitochondrial Health? With easy lifestyle changes, you can boost your mitochondrial health and increase energy production: Exercise Regularly : Physical activity generates new mitochondria and strengthens the existing ones. Keep moving with activities like walking, yoga, or weight training. Eat a Balanced Diet : Fuel your cells with antioxidant-rich foods like leafy greens, fish, and nuts. These nutrients support mitochondria and overall health while giving us more energy. Manage Stress : Chronic stress can damage mitochondria. Practice relaxation techniques like meditation, yoga, or deep breathing to keep stress levels in check. Consider Select Treatments and Supplements : NAD+ , B12 , Coenzyme Q10, magnesium, or alpha-lipoic acid can all be beneficial in supporting energy production and mitochondrial health. Recharge Your Batteries with Expert Help Optimizing your energy levels as you age doesn’t have to be a solo mission. Sometimes, we all need a little assistance—especially when it comes to something as important as your long-term health. A longevity specialist (like our team at AgelessRx) can help tailor a plan with the right balance of diet, exercise, and supplements. If you’re looking to increase your mitochondrial health and optimize your energy for years to come, try scheduling a longevity consultation with an AgelessRx prescriber. You can also explore our expert-curated energy and fatigue treatments, like NAD+ or B12 injections, both of which have been shown to potentially help improve energy  for more healthy, life-filled years. LDN 0.5 vs 1.5: What to Know Before You Buy | AgelessRx Skip to content Search for: Quick overview of what we’ll cover in this blog post: What to know before you buy LDN Why AgelessRx offers 2 starting doses The difference between 0.5mg & 1.5mg Who should start at which dose What to do if you want a different dose What to Know Before You Buy LDN Naltrexone is an enigmatic treatment whose benefits vary depending on which dosage you’re receiving. Just by the name alone, we can tell that Low Dose Naltrexone (LDN) is on the lower end of this spectrum, and its ideal use strays significantly from higher doses – namely, in how it affects our longevity. But the name shouldn’t suggest that there’s a single dose of LDN that’s considered the low dose. In fact, anything under 10mg of Naltrexone can be considered LDN. This begs the question: just how low do the doses go, and which dose is right for me? These questions are what drove us at AgelessRx to offer multiple starting doses for LDN. Below, we discuss the differences between these starting doses (0.5mg and 1.5mg), so you can make the most informed decision with your prescriber about what might be best for you. Here’s what to know before you buy LDN. Why the Low Dose? Many medications have different effects (and therefore different uses) when prescribed at higher or lower doses, and LDN is no exception. Naltrexone is most often prescribed to treat certain addictions at doses ranging from 50-150mg. When prescribed at these doses, Naltrexone acts as an antagonist to temporarily block the effects of certain drugs and naturally occurring dopamine, as well as the release of dopamine (the reward signal associated with drug addiction). When used at lower doses, though, Naltrexone appears to have a paradoxical effect that allows the brain to produce more endorphins, which help to improve pain relief. Additionally, lower doses of Naltrexone may also prevent overactivation of immune cells in the body and the brain (known as T-cells and microglia respectively), thereby blunting the destructive consequences of chronic inflammation. ORDER NOW Quick Order For experienced users or those who already know what they need, the Quick Order option allows you to bypass categories and quickly add and order tests we offer. ORDER NOW Most Popular Tests This section showcases the most frequently ordered tests by our users, offering insights into what tests others find most valuable for their health management. ORDER NOW Test by Body System If you're looking to monitor a specific body system (like cardiovascular or digestive), this option allows you to order relevant tests, ensuring a targeted approach to your health monitoring. ORDER NOW Search Tests ﻿ If you know the exact test you're looking for, use our search function. It's the quickest way to find and add a specific test to your order. ORDER NOW The 4 Ways to View Your Results Results Graphed Dynamically This viewing method allows you to see your test results in a dynamic graph format, visually tracking changes over time so that you can better understand your health trends. Results by Category This method organizes your test results by category, making it easier to navigate and understand them based on different areas of health or body systems. Functional Reference Ranges With functional reference ranges, you can view your test results in the context of optimal health ranges rather than just standard laboratory ranges. This can provide a more in-depth perspective on your health status. Results Report ﻿ This is a traditional lab report format provided by the lab, offering you a familiar layout of your results that is often used for sharing with healthcare providers. Unparalleled Access to Comprehensive Lab Testing with Ulta Lab Tests At Ulta Lab Tests, we pride ourselves on offering a broad array of diagnostic lab tests to cater to your diverse healthcare needs. With over 2,000 lab tests and 400 lab panels to choose from, our comprehensive suite of services ensures you're empowered with accurate, timely, and pertinent health information. Learn More Metabolic and Nutrient Tests Our metabolic and nutrient tests offer a deep dive into your body's metabolic processes, providing insights into your nutrient levels and ensuring your bodily functions are working optimally. From the Basic and Comprehensive Metabolic Panel Blood Tests (CMP Blood Test) that offer an overview of your body's chemical balance and metabolism to the Chemistry Panel (Chem Test) and Glucose Blood Tests, which screen for diabetes and pre-diabetes, we cover all bases. Our specific nutrient tests include Magnesium Blood Test, Vitamin B12 Blood Test, Vitamin D Blood Test, and 25-Hydroxy Vitamin D Blood Test. We also offer Urinalysis, which can detect early signs of diseases such as diabetes or kidney disease. Cardiac and Lipid Profile Tests Our cardiac and lipid profile tests ensure your heart health is never compromised. These include the Cardio IQ Tests, Cholesterol Blood Test, Lipid Panel Blood Test, and Triglycerides Blood Test that monitor risk factors for heart disease. We also offer the Apolipoprotein B Blood Test and Homocysteine Blood Test, known for their links to cardiovascular health, and the High Sensitivity C-Reactive Protein Blood Test (hs-CRP Blood Test) to identify inflammation, which can indicate a heightened risk for heart disease. Hormone and Endocrine Tests Hormones play a crucial role in our body's functioning. With our suite of hormone and endocrine tests, including Follicle-Stimulating Hormone Blood Test (FSH Blood Test), Luteinizing Hormone Blood Test (LH Blood Test), Progesterone Blood Test, Prolactin Blood Test, Testosterone Blood Test, Cortisol Blood Test, Human Chorionic Gonadotropin Blood Test (hCG Blood Test), Dehydroepiandrosterone Blood Test (DHEA Blood Test), Estradiol Blood Test, Estrogen Blood Test, and Insulin Blood Tests, you can ensure hormonal imbalances never go unnoticed. Thyroid Function Tests Our dedicated thyroid function tests, such as the Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone Blood Test (TSH Blood Test), Free Thyroxine Blood Test (T4, Free Blood Test), and Free Triiodothyronine Blood Test (T3, Free Blood Test), as well as Thyroglobulin Antibodies and Thyroid Peroxidase Blood Tests, provide a comprehensive view of your thyroid health, assisting in diagnosing and monitoring conditions like hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism. Inflammatory and Immunological Tests With inflammatory and immunological tests, we can help you monitor chronic inflammation and immune response conditions, such as rheumatoid arthritis or lupus. These tests include C-Reactive Protein Blood Test (CRP Blood Test) and High Sensitivity C-Reactive Protein Blood Test (hs-CRP Blood Test), along with Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate Blood Test (Sed Rate Blood Test). Liver and Kidney Function Tests Our Hepatic Function Panel and Hepatitis Blood Tests, along with the Uric Acid Blood Test and Amylase Blood Tests, can help you keep a check on your liver and kidney health, enabling the early detection of conditions such as liver disease, gout or kidney disorders. Blood Health and Anemia Tests Our suite of blood health and anemia tests, including the Complete Blood Count Blood Test (CBC Blood Test), Iron & TIBC Blood Test, Ferritin Blood Tests, and Prothrombin Time with INR Blood Test, help identify blood-related disorders such as anemia, infection, hemophilia, blood clotting conditions, and monitor blood thinning therapy. Cancer Marker Tests We offer cancer marker tests like the Prostate-Specific Antigen Blood Test (PSA Blood Test), which can assist in identifying the early signs of prostate cancer, aiding in your proactive health management strategy. Gastrointestinal Tests Our gastrointestinal tests, such as the Amylase Blood Test, Lipase Blood Test, and Celiac Blood Test, are geared towards detecting digestive disorders like pancreatitis, celiac disease, and other gut-related conditions. Infectious Disease Tests Our portfolio of infectious disease tests, including Hepatitis B Blood Test, Measles Blood Test, Mumps Blood Test, Rubella Blood Test, Varicella Blood Test, Tuberculosis Blood Test (TB Blood Test), and Varicella Blood Test, can help you ensure you and your loved ones remain safeguarded against these diseases. Pregnancy and Fertility Tests Our pregnancy test and fertility tests, such as Human Chorionic Gonadotropin Blood Test (hCG Blood Test), Progesterone Blood Test, Follicle-Stimulating Hormone Blood Test (FSH Blood Test), Luteinizing Hormone Blood Test (LH Blood Test), Estradiol Blood Test, Estrogen Blood Test, and Prolactin Blood Test, support your journey towards parenthood by providing valuable insights about your reproductive health. What Are SARMS? - We Have SARMS For Sale A Selective androgen receptor modulator (SARM) is a type of drug that is designed to selectively bind to androgen receptors in specific tissues, such as muscle and bone. This means that SARMs can have anabolic effects (building muscle) without the same androgenic effects (masculinizing effects) as testosterone. SARMs were first developed in the early 1990s after Dalton and Miller, who discovered that aryl propionamides with structural similarities to bicalutamide and hydroxyflutamide could activate AR-dependent transcriptional activity provided the early lead for the development of diaryl propionamide class of SARMs. However, SARMs are not currently approved for use in humans, and there is a limited amount of research on their safety and efficacy. The potential benefits of SARMs include their anabolic effects without the same androgenic effects as testosterone. This could make them useful for treating conditions such as muscle wasting and osteoporosis. However, the potential risks of SARMs include liver toxicity, cardiovascular disease, and prostate cancer. Different Types of SARMS The majority of SARMs found in the market can typically be encountered in three distinct variations: Powder SARMS: Initially, all SARMs exist as a powdered substance, which is then transformed into either tablet, encased within capsules, or converted into a liquid form. Every SARM initially starts in a powder state. This is the reason many researchers regard powdered SARMs as the most unadulterated version of these medicinal compounds. Powdered SARMs can be effortlessly portioned into the specific quantity needed by the investigator. Gel SARMS: GEL SARMs enjoy considerable popularity as well. They are also referred to as SARMs Capsules.  The enthusiasm primarily stems from the convenience of not needing to measure out capsules, thus making the process more straightforward for researchers. GEL SARMs maintain their initial purity for extended durations. GEL also safeguards the strength of the encapsulated ingredients. This guarantees the uniformity and effectiveness of each individual dose. Active components in liquids have been observed to diminish in potency over time. Liquid SARMS: Liquid SARMs are recognized for their exceptional purity and extended half-life. When appropriately stored, they possess a lengthy shelf life and can be effortlessly measured and preserved. Liquid SARMs hold a distinctive appeal for researchers due to the ease of measuring precise quantities for administration to subjects, with or without water. They demonstrate potential in their respective research fields for those who find it challenging to utilize capsules or pills, particularly when working with animals. What is a Certificate of Analysis (COA)? A Certificate of Analysis (COA) is a document produced by an independent or in-house analytical laboratory verifying a compound’s identity, purity, and concentration using methods like HPLC, LC-MS, or NMR. What is High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC)? HPLC is a laboratory technique that separates components in a mixture by passing solvent under high pressure through a column to quantify purity or detect contaminants. What is Liquid Chromatography–Mass Spectrometry (LC-MS)? LC-MS combines liquid chromatography with mass spectrometry to separate, identify, and quantify molecular species by mass-to-charge ratio. What does ≥ 99% purity mean? ≥ 99% purity indicates that 99 percent or more of a sample is the target analyte; impurities (≤1%) are the detectable residual substances. What does “Research Use Only” (RUO) mean? Research Use Only (RUO) means the compound is explicitly for laboratory, analytical, or experimental use—not for medical, diagnostic, or human consumption. Focus on Nootropics – Why They Matter in Research Nootropics (also known as “cognitive enhancers”) are molecules studied for their effects on brain function, memory, focus, and neuroprotection.
